4. Create a REST controller to handle HTTP requests and define endpoints for your application.

5. ResponseEntity lets us control the HTTP response properly
	:- Instead of every API returning random formats, all future endpoints can return a consistent structure:

        {
          "success": true,
          "message": "...",
          "data": "...",
          "timestamp": "..."
        }

	For example:
	ResponseEntity.ok(...)
	means:
	HTTP 200 OK

6. Record is a compact Java class used for immutable data objects.

                  This:
                  ApiResponse<T>
                  means the response can hold any type of data.
                  Example:
                  ApiResponse<String>
                  ApiResponse<Tenant>
                  ApiResponse<List<User>>

                  So later, if we return a tenant object, we can do:
                  ApiResponse<TenantResponse>

7. New dependencies added:
	- spring-boot-starter-data-jpa : Adds JPA and Hibernate support. This lets Java classes map to database tables.
	- h2 : Adds the H2 database engine.
	- spring-boot-h2console : Adds the browser-based H2 console support required in Spring Boot 4.
	- hibernate : implementation used by Spring Boot

8. Added database entity: Tenant
	Why we added it

    In a multi-tenant SaaS system, almost every business object will eventually belong to a tenant.

    For example, later we may have:

    Tenant → Users
    Tenant → Roles
    Tenant → Projects
    Tenant → Subscriptions
    Tenant → Settings

     :- @Entity means: This Java class maps to a database table.
     :- @Id means: This field is the primary key.
     :- @GeneratedValue means: The database will automatically generate a unique value for this field when a new record is inserted.
     :- @PrePersist runs before the record is first saved.
     :- @PreUpdate runs before the record is updated.

9. Added:
	TenantRepository → database access
    TenantService    → business logic
    TenantController → API endpoints
    Tenant DTOs      → clean request/response objects

    This is the standard Spring Boot flow:
    Client → Controller → Service → Repository → Database

    JpaRepository<Tenant, UUID> gives us ready-made database methods:
    save()
    findAll()
    findById()
    deleteById()
    existsById()

    The custom methods:
    	findBySlug(String slug);
    	existsBySlug(String slug);
    are automatically implemented by Spring Data JPA based on their method names.